The official seal of Wichita State University anchors the ceremonial anaglyph and is encircled by two hyperbolic forms designed to complement the university mace. The presidential medallion is suspended from black silk trimmed with gold. The University Mace As the official symbol of the university’s authority and power, the mace is carried by selected college faculty in the academic procession. The mace was commissioned in 1978 by Paul J. Magelli, former dean of Fairmount College of Liberal Arts and Sciences, as a memorial to his twin brother, Peter M. Magelli, and presented for the first time at the 1980 commencement. Designed by artist Jonathan Graham Bonner of Providence, Rhode Island, the mace is executed primarily in stainless steel, gold and silver. The head of the mace is a gilt frame with 22 stainless steel spikes. The points are sterling silver. A silver ball engraved with the three seals of Wichita State University—Fairmount College, the Municipal University of Wichita and Wichita State University—is suspended in the frame by two springs. The shaft is a stainless steel spring, and the handle is a gilt ball set with nine hematites. The University Seal The seal of Wichita State University incorporates many images. A farmer and an Indian, representing Kansas’ rural background and Native American heritage, are looking up at seven stars above a lamp of learning. The university’s name arcs above these images. Below them is a sunflower flanked by wheat, again signifying Kansas, and a laurel, a symbol of learning. Three significant dates of the university’s past also are included: 1895, Fairmount College founding; 1926, University of Wichita reorganization date; and 1964, the date the university entered the Kansas Regents’ system. Commencement Notes Honorary Degrees An honorary degree is an exceptional honor bestowed upon a person without fulfllment of the usual requirements. Honorary degrees are conferred only upon persons of notable intellectual, scholarly, professional, creative achievement or service to humanity. A candidate for an honorary degree must be deeply grounded in a career of scholarship, research, creative activity, service to humanity or other profession consistent with the endeavors of Wichita State University. Date of Graduation This program is not an official list of confrmed graduates for the 2025 Spring Commencement. Students listed in this commencement program are candidates for degrees in Spring and Summer 2025. Students’ names are listed in this program as they appear on the graduation list provided by the Office of the Registrar. Students’ names are read during the university commencement ceremony as they appear in the graduation information approved by the graduates. Graduation with Honors Degrees are conferred with distinction upon undergraduate students who have shown exceptional scholarship in both their cumulative and WSU grade point averages. Students with grade point averages of 3.90 out of a possible 4.00 receive the summa cum laude award; those with averages of 3.550 to 3.899 receive the magna cum laude; and those with averages of 3.250 to 3.549 receive the cum laude. Candidates for degrees and for university honors for Spring and Summer 2025 have been tentatively determined on the basis of work completed through Fall 2024. In addition to university honors, departmental honors are awarded to students who have met the appropriate requirements. Wichita State does not confer honors upon students completing degrees in the Graduate School. Academic Dress Today’s academic dress evolved from caps and gowns worn in medieval universities. The academic gown is the basic garment and by tradition is black for all degrees and ranks. The square caps or mortarboards are part of the prescribed academic dress. Accompanying the gowns are hoods lined with silk in the ofcial color of the institution conferring the degree and bordered in the color representing the discipline of learning. The color of the tassel designates the student’s degree and may vary from what is found on the hood. Students receiving graduate degrees wear the color appropriate to the degree emphasis. Drab • W. Commencement Guest Neelima Parasker, Kansas Board of Regents Neelima Parasker was appointed to the Kansas Board of Regents by Governor Laura Kelly in 2023. Regent Parasker is the President and Chief Executive Officer of SnapIT Solutions LLC, an innovative technology company providing IT services, software product development solutions, training, and staffing. With more than 20 years of experience in IT, she has held many leadership positions. She is a Board Member of KansasWorks State Workforce Board and served on the Community Development Advisory Council at the Federal Reserve Bank of Kansas City. Regent Parasker studied at Osmania University, India, where she earned a Bachelor of Science in Mechanical Engineering. She later earned her Master of Science in Computer Science from Oklahoma City University. She serves as the Executive Director of Wichita Habitat for Humanity, working toward a world where everyone has a decent place to live, and is the principal owner of Inclusive Growth Strategies, a consulting ﬁrm dedicated to fostering inclusive and equitable communities. For over two decades, Danielle has dedicated her career to empowering communities through education, advocacy, access, and mobilization. She has developed and implemented programs, facilitated critical conversations, and provided training to enrich organizations and strengthen communities. Her leadership extends across various sectors, and she currently serves on numerous boards, including the Wichita Regional Chamber of Commerce Leadership Wichita Board of Trustees (Chair), Community Operations Recovery Empowerment (Vice Chair), the Habitat Kansas Affiliate Organization, and the United Way Coalition to End Homelessness, to name a few. Danielle’s commitment to leadership and lifelong learning is reﬂected in her participation in esteemed programs such as Advance Kansas, the Kansas Leadership Center, Young Professionals of Wichita Leadership Academy, Leadership Wichita, and Leadership Kansas. As a proud alumna of USD 259 public schools, Danielle pursued higher education at Wichita State University, earning a bachelor’s degree in psychology and a master’s degree in public administration. Her time at WSU included instrumental contributions to transitioning the Office of Multicultural Affairs into the Office of Diversity and Inclusion—creating a space where students, faculty, and staff could embrace differences, engage in critical dialogue, and celebrate the vibrant cultures that make up the university community. Beyond her professional and civic contributions, Danielle holds her role as a devoted spouse and mother as her greatest honor. She and her husband, Wichita District 1 Councilmember Brandon Johnson, have a young adult and two children—Khairi, Aria, and Arin—with a shared commitment to servant leadership. Her work continues to be driven by the mantra she lives by: “Think, Speak, and Act for yourself and your community.” She has a profound passion for fostering a thriving community through collaboration and collective action. As a mutually owned, not-for-profit health plan, BCBSKS serves nearly one million members with the state’s largest provider network and award-winning customer service. As a sixth-generation Kansan, All brings nearly three decades of experience in leadership and service to his role. All joined BCBSKS in 2006 as its General Counsel. Over the next decade, he had the opportunity to learn and oversee nearly every area of the company. In April 2018, he became the eighth President and CEO in the company’s history. Prior to joining BCBSKS, All spent several years in private legal practice before serving in state government in Kansas as Assistant Insurance Commissioner and Chief Counsel to Governor Kathleen Sebelius. All is strongly committed to serving Kansas communities. He served as the first chairman of the board of the United Way of Kaw Valley. He serves as Treasurer of the Greater Topeka Partnership and on the Executive Committee of the Greater Wichita Partnership. He served as chair of the University of Kansas Honors Program Advisory Board, and chair of the Topeka Chamber of Commerce. For 16 years, he taught at the University of Kansas School of Law. All grew up in Augusta, Kansas. He received his bachelor’s degree from the University of Kansas and his law degree from Yale Law School. Frank Barton School of Business College of Engineering Guest Speaker Laura Bernstorf Laura Bernstorf is a distinguished leader in the aerospace industry, currently serving as the Director of Special Missions Program Management at Textron Aviation. With over two decades of experience, Laura has successfully managed complex technical development and integration projects with international cross-functional teams. Laura’s brings experience from previous roles at Viaanix Inc., an IoT tech startup, and at Airbus Americas, Inc., where she led innovative projects and strategic initiatives. She has also contributed to academia as an Honors College Lecturer at Wichita State University, fostering interdisciplinary research and innovation. An advocate for community engagement, Laura has served on various boards, including the Wichita State University Alumni Association, AbilityPoint, and Cars for Charities. Her dedication to mentoring and career development is evident through her involvement in numerous leadership programs and her commitment to supporting young professionals. Laura holds a Master’s in Innovation Design and a Bachelor’s in Industrial Engineering from Wichita State University. She is a certified Project Management Professional (PMP) and has received several awards for her contributions to the industry and community including the Wichita Urban Professionals Civic Leadership Award, Wichita Business Journal’s 40 Under 40, and the WSU Young Alumni Award.
